  <p>QR codes are everywhere in 2026. From restaurant menus and product packaging to business cards and event tickets, these small square barcodes have become an essential part of how we share information. The good news is that creating a QR code is completely free and takes less than a minute. In this guide, you will learn everything you need to know about making QR codes that work.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">What Is a QR Code?</h2>
  <p>A QR (Quick Response) code is a two-dimensional barcode that stores data such as URLs, text, phone numbers, or Wi-Fi credentials. When someone scans it with their smartphone camera, they are instantly directed to the encoded information. Unlike traditional barcodes that hold only a few digits, QR codes can store up to 4,296 alphanumeric characters, making them incredibly versatile.</p>
  <p class="mt-3">QR codes were invented in 1994 by a Japanese automotive company but gained mainstream adoption during the pandemic when contactless interactions became the norm. Today, virtually every smartphone can read QR codes natively through the built-in camera app, so there is no special software required for your audience to use them.</p>

