  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Popular Use Cases for QR Codes</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Business Cards</h3>
  <p>Add a QR code to your business card that links to your LinkedIn profile, portfolio website, or a digital vCard. This makes it easy for new contacts to save your information instantly rather than manually typing it in.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Restaurant Menus</h3>
  <p>Print a QR code on table tents or stickers so diners can view your menu on their phone. This reduces printing costs, allows you to update the menu without reprinting, and provides a hygienic contactless experience.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Marketing and Advertising</h3>
  <p>Place QR codes on flyers, posters, product packaging, or billboards to direct people to landing pages, special offers, or app downloads. QR codes bridge the gap between physical marketing materials and your online presence.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Event Tickets and Check-In</h3>
  <p>Use QR codes for event entry. Each attendee receives a unique code that can be scanned at the door for fast, paperless check-in. This reduces wait times and eliminates the need for physical tickets.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Wi-Fi Sharing</h3>
  <p>Encode your Wi-Fi network name and password into a QR code. Guests can scan it to connect instantly without asking for the password. This is particularly useful for hotels, cafes, and coworking spaces.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Tips for Effective QR Codes</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mt-4">
    <li><strong>Test before printing</strong> &mdash; Always scan your QR code with multiple devices to make sure it works correctly before sending it to print.</li>
    <li><strong>Maintain contrast</strong> &mdash; Use dark colors on a light background. Low contrast makes it harder for cameras to read the code. Black on white is the most reliable combination.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep a quiet zone</strong> &mdash; Leave some white space around the QR code. Crowding it with other design elements can interfere with scanning.</li>
    <li><strong>Use short URLs</strong> &mdash; Shorter URLs produce simpler QR codes with fewer modules, which are easier to scan, especially at smaller sizes.</li>
    <li><strong>Size matters</strong> &mdash; For print, the QR code should be at least 2 cm x 2 cm (about 0.8 inches). For billboards or signs that will be scanned from a distance, increase the size proportionally.</li>
    <li><strong>Add a call to action</strong> &mdash; Place text near the code like "Scan to view menu" or "Scan for a discount." People are more likely to scan when they know what to expect.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Static vs. Dynamic QR Codes</h2>
  <p>Static QR codes encode data directly into the pattern. Once created, the content cannot be changed. They are perfect for permanent information like a website URL or contact details.</p>
  <p class="mt-3">Dynamic QR codes use a short redirect URL that points to your destination. This allows you to change where the code leads without generating a new one. Dynamic codes typically require a paid service. For most personal and small business uses, static QR codes work perfectly and our free generator creates them in seconds.</p>

